    "content_hash": "sha256:52483d26c7f7b61a3f7a8cdea493c623214dfd2d06a5b090e04249148f8adb91",
    "summary": "Wu Zetian (624–705 AD) was the only woman in Chinese history to assume the title of Empress Regnant — ruling in her own name as the legitimate sovereign rather than as regent or empress consort — and her reign represents one of the most remarkable political careers in world history. Beginning as a concubine of Emperor Taizong of the [[event:87|Tang Dynasty]], Wu maneuvered her way to power with ruthless political skill over decades, becoming the dominant force behind two emperors (her sons) before declaring herself the founding emperor of her own dynasty, the Zhou, in 690 AD.\n\nWu Zetian's forty-year dominance (660–705 AD) was marked by both effective governance and political terror. On the positive side, she expanded the civil service examination system, reducing the power of the old aristocratic families by opening government office to talented men of lower birth — a genuinely meritocratic reform that strengthened the Tang state. She extended Tang borders, sponsored Buddhism (building great temple complexes and commissioning the famous Longmen Grottoes Buddhist carvings), and presided over a period of prosperity and stability. On the negative side, she employed networks of spies and informers, executed officials, nobles, and family members who posed threats to her rule, and her use of brutal interrogation methods to eliminate opponents was notorious even by the standards of imperial Chinese politics. She was forced to abdicate in 705 AD by a palace coup that restored the Tang dynasty, and died shortly after. Chinese historical tradition, dominated by Confucian values hostile to female political power, gave her a predominantly negative legacy, though modern reassessments have been more balanced.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wu_Zetian",
